The '''Quantified Self'''<ref>{{cite web|last=Gary|first=Wolf|title=QS & The Macroscope|url=http://aether.com/themacroscope|accessdate=10 February 2013}}</ref>  is a movement to incorporate technology into data acquisition on aspects of a person's daily life in terms of inputs (e.g. food consumed, quality of surrounding air), states (e.g. mood, [[skin conductance|arousal]], [[pulse oximetry|blood oxygen levels]]), and performance ([[cognitive test|mental]] and physical).  Such self-monitoring and self-sensing, which combines wearable sensors (EEG, ECG, video, etc.) and [[wearable computing]], is also known as [[lifelogging]] or [[sousveillance]]. Other names for using self-tracking data to improve daily functioning<ref>{{cite web|last=Dorminey|first=Bruce|title=Tic-Toc-Trac: New Watch Gadget Measures Time Perception For The Self-Quantifying|url=http://www.forbes.com/sites/brucedorminey/2012/05/31/tic-toc-trac-new-watch-gadget-measures-time-perception-for-the-self-quantifying/|publisher=[[Forbes]]|authorlink=Bruce Dorminey|date=2012-05-31}}</ref> are “self-tracking”, "auto-analytics", “body hacking” and “self-quantifying”.<ref>{{cite web|title=Counting every moment|url=http://www.economist.com/node/21548493|publisher=[[The Economist]]|date=Mar 3rd 2012}}</ref>

==History==
The history of self-tracking using wearable sensors combined with [[wearable computing]] and wireless communication, dates back many years, and appeared, in the form of sousveillance (wearable physiological sensors, etc.) in the 1970s.<ref>Intelligent Image Processing, Steve Mann, John Wiley and Sons, 2001</ref><ref>{{Cite journal 
