}}</ref><ref>Persuasive Technology and Digital Design for Behaviour Change, Dan Lockton, Brunel University - Brunel Design; University of Warwick - WMG, August 7, 2012</ref><ref>WEB 2.0, VIGILÂNCIA E MONITORAMENTO: ENTRE FUNÇÕES PÓSMASSIVAS E CLASSIFICAÇÃO SOCIAL, Tarcízio Silva, Universidade Federal da Bahia</ref> The term "quantified self" appears to have been proposed by [[Wired Magazine]] editors [[Gary Wolf (journalist)|Gary Wolf]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Singer|first=Emily|title=The Measured Life|url=http://www.technologyreview.com/biomedicine/37784/|publisher=[[Massachusetts Institute of Technology{{!}}MIT]]|accessdate=2011-07-05}}</ref> and [[Kevin Kelly (editor)|Kevin Kelly]]<ref name=aetherqs>{{cite web|last=Wolf|first=Gary|title=Quantified Self|url=http://aether.com/quantifiedself|publisher=Gary Wolf|accessdate=2012-03-26|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/66TEHdz4d|archivedate=2012-03-26}}</ref> in 2007<ref>{{cite web|title=Quantified Self Blog, oldest entries|url=http://quantifiedself.com/2007/page/3/|accessdate=2012-03-26|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/66TEY49wv|archivedate=2012-03-26}}</ref> as "a collaboration of users and tool makers who share an interest in self knowledge through self-tracking." In 2010, Wolf spoke about the movement at [[TED (conference)|TED]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Wolf|first=Gary|title=The quantified self|url=http://www.ted.com/talks/gary_wolf_the_quantified_self.html|publisher=[[TED (conference)]]|accessdate=2012-03-26}}</ref> and in May 2011 the first international conference was held in [[Mountain View, California]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Invasion of the body hackers|url=http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/2/3ccb11a0-923b-11e0-9e00-00144feab49a.html|publisher=[[Financial Times]]|date=2011-06-10|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/66TFDLCSY|archivedate=2012-03-26}}</ref>

Today the global community has over a hundred groups in 31 countries around the world.<ref>http://quantified-self.meetup.com/</ref>

==Methodologies==
The primary methodology of self-quantification is data collection, followed by visualization, cross-referencing and the discovery of correlations.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hesse|first=Monica|title=Bytes of Life|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/09/08/AR2008090802681_pf.html|publisher=Washington Post|accessdate=2012-03-26|date=September 9, 2008}}</ref>

Life-tracking information from various applications can be difficult to integrate and find meaning.  Websites such as [http://quantimodo.com/ Quantimodo] can help by synergizing, visualizing, and analyzing the cacophony data to identify correlations between specific input factors and treatments (independent variables) and mood outcomes (dependent variables). The [[Pearson product-moment correlation coefficient]] derived from an XY [[scatterplot]] of input behaviours and output states can quantify the effectiveness of various treatments.

The human mind is not powerful enough to keep track of the countless factors that go into producing an emotional state. Timeline graphical analysis can help to identify potential confounding uncontrolled variables that may be contaminating the results of an experiment.  

Fine-grained, personalized minimum effective dosages of drugs can be established.  Degrees of drug tolerance and withdrawal symptoms can be quantified.  By integrating the area under the mood curves, true cost-benefit analyses weighing therapeutic benefits against adverse effects can be performed.

